,Not Recommended,235620,8417966,"Posted: 29 December, 2013",all,Nilesy @ Twitch,"Small World 2 is a tablet port of the board game ""Small World"", of critical acclaim.Sadly, I cannot recommend this game, and warn those to proceed with trepedation.The game feels as though it is meant to be played ""once in a while"", multiplayer, via e-mail with a friend. I say this because every single time you tab out of the game, if you are playing live, you need to watch the moves of those who played after your last turn over and over again. Every single time. Even if you tab out for a few seconds. What this boils down to is that if you and 4 friends are playing (as was our case) 80% of the time spent ""playing"" the game translates to watching back previous moves while you laboriously await your turn. This is hopefully something that could be patched/fixed, but as this is a direct port from a tablet variant I don't foresee this happening.Next up, if you don't know how to play Small World, don't in any way expect this game to teach you. Thankfully, we had a seasoned pro of Small World playing with us so we had some idea what was going on, but the shear lack of tooltips, information and tutelage was kind of staggering. I'd say this is the type of game that is a) aimed towards someone who already plays Small World and b) a tablet device or phone.The controls, the feel, and the entirity of the game just scream tablet game. And that's great! On a tablet. Sadly, as a PC title, it falls short.After enduring one hour long game with my friends, I immediately requested a Steam refund for this severely underwhelming game, which was rejected as I'd already used the title, so for everyone else out there: beware.The title has great promise! Small World is a GREAT board game, but this digital port just does not deliver. Maybe the devs will pick this up and adapt it, and if so I'll happily edit my review and re-review the title; after all, Small World itself is a great game! But for now, again, beware.Nilesy"
